BANDIT:
ğŸ›¡ï¸ BANDIT FULL REVIEW FLOW

1.Hereâ€™s a complete Bandit review process from start to end, tailored for DevSecOps automation in GitHub Actions.
This includes local use, CI/CD integration, strict security gates, and best practices.

ğŸ”¹ 1. What is Bandit?
Bandit is a Python static analysis tool that finds common security issues in Python code â€” like:
eval() usage
subprocess misuse
hardcoded passwords
weak hashing (e.g., MD5)
insecure file handling

ğŸ”¹ 2. Install Bandit (Local or CI)
âœ… Locally (Linux/macOS)
c:pip install bandit

âœ… In CI (e.g., GitHub Actions)
- name: Install Bandit
  run: pip install bandit

ğŸ”¹ 3. Run Bandit (Basic Command)
ğŸ” Scan entire repo:
bandit -r . -ll

ğŸ” Scan specific folder:
bandit -r scripts/ -ll

ğŸ’¬ Flags:
-r: recursive
-ll: show Low, Medium, High issues
-q: quiet output (good for CI logs)
--format json: machine-readable output

ğŸ”¹ 4. Sample Output
>> Issue: [B403:blacklist] Consider possible security implications associated with subprocess module.
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: High
   Location: script.py:14

ğŸ”¹ 5. GitHub Actions Integration Example

# .github/workflows/bandit-scan.yml
name: Bandit Security Scan

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
  pull_request:
    branches: [main]

jobs:
  security:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - uses: actions/checkout@v3

    - name: Set up Python
      uses: actions/setup-python@v4
      with:
        python-version: '3.11'

    - name: Install Bandit
      run: pip install bandit

    - name: Run Bandit scan
      run: bandit -r . -ll -q

ğŸ”¹ 6. Enforce Pipeline Failure on Security Issues

- name: Run Bandit (Strict Mode)
  run: |
    bandit -r . -ll -q || exit 1
â¡ï¸ This ensures that if Bandit finds any vulnerabilities, the GitHub Actions workflow fails.


ğŸ”¹ 7. Best Practices
| Practice                     | Description                                                        |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| âœ… Pre-commit hook            | Add Bandit to Git pre-commit to stop risky code early.             |
| âœ… Use `# nosec`              | To skip a line intentionally (add a reason in code comments).      |
| âœ… Integrate with other tools | Pair Bandit with Trivy, Snyk, etc., for full DevSecOps.            |
| ğŸ“ Ignore files              | Create `.bandit` or use `--exclude` to skip safe/irrelevant files. |
| ğŸ” Automate                  | Run on every PR/push to main or dev branch.                        |


ğŸ”¹ 8. Add Custom Configuration (Optional)
.bandit config file:
[bandit]
skips: B101,B102
exclude: tests,venv

ğŸ”¹ 9. Example Bandit Errors to Watch For
| Bandit Code | Description                      | Severity |
| ----------- | -------------------------------- | -------- |
| B101        | Use of `assert`                  | Medium   |
| B102        | Use of `exec`                    | High     |
| B403        | Insecure `subprocess` usage      | Medium   |
| B303        | Use of insecure hash (e.g., MD5) | High     |


âœ… Summary: Bandit Integration = Secure Python Code
| Stage           | Command or Config            |   |                                |
| --------------- | ---------------------------- | - | ------------------------------ |
| Local install   | `pip install bandit`         |   |                                |
| Scan code       | `bandit -r . -ll`            |   |                                |
| GitHub Actions  | Full workflow as shown above |   |                                |
| Block on issues | Add \`                       |   | exit 1\` to enforce CI failure |
| Custom config   | Add `.bandit` file           |   |                                |


Generate a .bandit config file ?
Hereâ€™s a clean and practical .bandit config file tailored for most DevSecOps projects. It includes:
Skipping safe files like tests/, venv/, migrations/
Disabling a few noisy or non-relevant Bandit rules (optional)
Clear structure for customization

âœ… .bandit File (Save at Project Root)
[bandit]
# Directories to exclude from the scan
exclude: 
    tests,
    venv,
    .venv,
    migrations,
    __pycache__,
    node_modules

# Optional: Skip noisy rules (customize as needed)
skips:
    B101,  # assert statements (okay in tests)
    B311,  # random (use for non-crypto ops only)
    B404,  # subprocess module (manually reviewed)

# Report settings
verbosity: 1
confidence: HIGH
severity: MEDIUM

# Format for output (useful for CI)
format: screen

ğŸ” How to Use It with Bandit
Now run Bandit with:
bandit -r . -c .bandit

Or add to your GitHub Actions:
- name: Run Bandit with config
  run: bandit -r . -c .bandit -q

ğŸ›¡ï¸ Tip: Customize Based on Use Case
You can remove any skips if you want stricter security. For example:
Remove B101 if you want to ban all assert statements in production code.
Keep B404 only if you want to manually approve subprocess usage.


QUESTION:
1.Combine Bandit with Trivy and Snyk in a single GitHub Actions pipeline?

Perfect. Here's a complete DevSecOps GitHub Actions pipeline that runs:

âœ… Security Scanners in One Workflow:
Bandit â†’ Python code security (static analysis)
Trivy â†’ Dependency, secrets, and config scanning
Snyk â†’ Deep open source dependency scan

ğŸ›¡ï¸ Unified DevSecOps Security Workflow
(.github/workflows/devsecops-scan.yml)

name: DevSecOps Security Scan

on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
  pull_request:
    branches: [main]

jobs:
  security-scan:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
    - name: Checkout Repository
      uses: actions/checkout@v3

    - name: Set up Python
      uses: actions/setup-python@v4
      with:
        python-version: '3.11'

    - name: Install Bandit
      run: pip install bandit

    - name: Run Bandit Scan
      run: |
        echo "ğŸ” Running Bandit..."
        bandit -r . -c .bandit -q || exit 1

    - name: Install Trivy
      run: |
        sudo apt-get install wget apt-transport-https gnupg lsb-release -y
        wget -qO - https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb/public.key | sudo apt-key add -
        echo "deb https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy-repo/deb $(lsb_release -sc) main" | sudo tee -a /etc/apt/sources.list.d/trivy.list
        sudo apt-get update
        sudo apt-get install trivy -y

    - name: Run Trivy File System Scan
      run: |
        echo "ğŸ” Running Trivy file system scan..."
        trivy fs . --exit-code 1 --severity HIGH,CRITICAL || exit 1

    - name: Run Trivy Secrets Scan
      run: |
        echo "ğŸ” Scanning for secrets with Trivy..."
        trivy fs . --scanners secret --exit-code 1 || exit 1

    - name: Run Trivy Dependency Scan
      run: |
        echo "ğŸ“¦ Scanning dependencies with Trivy..."
        trivy config . --exit-code 1 --severity HIGH,CRITICAL || exit 1

    - name: Install Snyk CLI
      run: |
        npm install -g snyk

    - name: Authenticate Snyk
      run: snyk auth ${{ secrets.SNYK_TOKEN }}

    - name: Run Snyk Dependency Scan
      run: |
        echo "ğŸ” Running Snyk..."
        snyk test --severity-threshold=medium || exit 1


ğŸ” Prerequisite: Add SNYK_TOKEN to GitHub Secrets
Go to your repo â†’ Settings > Secrets and Variables > Actions
Click New repository secret
Name: SNYK_TOKEN
Value: your Snyk API token from https://snyk.io/account/

ğŸ§ª What This Pipeline Does:
| Tool   | Function                           | Exit on Failure |
| ------ | ---------------------------------- | --------------- |
| Bandit | Python security linting            | âœ…               |
| Trivy  | FS scan + secrets + IaC            | âœ…               |
| Snyk   | Vulnerability scan on dependencies | âœ…               |

ğŸ“¦ Optional Additions:
Auto-notifications via Slack/Email
Trivy Docker image scans
HTML/JSON reports upload
Retry logic or matrix scanning


